ut national identity. At the same time, the book emphasizes the global, exploring the impact of international cultural products on national identity construction, the complexities of Americanisation, and Britain's place in a transnational system of production and consumption that forged the dances of the Jazz Age.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aDancezGreat BritainxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  aAmericanisation.  aEnglish style.  aLambeth Walk.  aautonomy.  aballroom dancing.  acommodification.  aconsumption practices.  adance hall industry.  adance profession.  aforeign dance.  anational identity.  anovelty dances.  apopular dance.  awartime Britain.1 aAbra, Allison, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2017 eBook-Packagez978311128281740uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152610594340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526105943423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526105943/original  a978-3-11-128281-7  Manchester University Press 2017 eBook-Packageb2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles